<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>

<chapter xml:id="ch13-word-perfect" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Word Perfect</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In the previous chapter we mastered some of the most basic and important functions
      for examining and manipulating text. Now we are in a position to analyze the actual
      words that appear in text documents. Some of the most basic functions of the Internet,
      such as keyword search, are accomplished by analyzing the <q>content,</q> i.e., the
      words in a body of text.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-word-cloud-intro">
    <title>Word Clouds and the Corpus</title>

    <p>
      A <term>corpus</term>, from the Latin word meaning <q>body,</q> is a word that text
      analysts use to refer to a body of text material, often consisting of one or more
      documents. When thinking about a corpus of textual data, a set of documents could
      really be anything: web pages, word processing documents on your computer, a set of
      tweets, or government reports.
    </p>

    <p>
      In this chapter we will use some new R packages to extend our abilities to work with
      text and to build our own word cloud from data retrieved from Twitter. Before beginning
      our work, we can improve the quality of the display by taking out a lot of junk that
      won't make sense to show in the word cloud. We have authored a function called
      <c>CleanTweets()</c> that strips out extra spaces, gets rid of all URL strings, takes
      out the retweet header, removes hashtags, and eliminates references to other people's
      tweet handles:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch13-cleantweets">
      <code>
CleanTweets &lt;- function(tweets)
{
  tweets &lt;- str_replace_all(tweets, "  ", " ")
  tweets &lt;- str_replace_all(tweets,
    "http://t.co/[a-z,A-Z,0-9]{8}", "")
  tweets &lt;- str_replace(tweets, "RT @[a-z,A-Z]*: ", "")
  tweets &lt;- str_replace_all(tweets, "#[a-z,A-Z]*", "")
  tweets &lt;- str_replace_all(tweets, "@[a-z,A-Z]*", "")
  return(tweets)
}
      </code>
    </program>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch13-clean-run">
      <code>
cleanText &lt;- tweetDF$text
cleanText &lt;- CleanTweets(cleanText)
head(cleanText, 10)
      </code>
    </program>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-term-doc-matrix">
    <title>The Term-Document Matrix</title>

    <p>
      A <term>term-document matrix</term> is a rectangular array of numbers where each row
      is a term (word) and each column is a document (in our case, a tweet). The value in
      each cell is the count of how many times that term appears in that document. We can
      use the R package called <c>tm</c> (short for <q>text mining</q>) to build this
      structure for us. Begin by installing and loading the <c>tm</c> package:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch13-tm">
      <code>
EnsurePackage("tm")
tweetCorpus &lt;- Corpus(VectorSource(cleanText))
tweetTDM &lt;- TermDocumentMatrix(tweetCorpus,
  control=list(removePunctuation=TRUE,
               stopwords=TRUE))
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      The first step creates a corpus object from our vector of cleaned tweet texts. The
      <c>TermDocumentMatrix()</c> function takes the corpus and returns the matrix. Two
      important control options are <c>removePunctuation</c> and <c>stopwords</c>. Stop
      words are very common words such as <q>the,</q> <q>a,</q> <q>is,</q> and
      <q>of</q> that are so common that they are not informative. Removing stop words
      keeps the term-document matrix from being dominated by these unremarkable words.
    </p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-word-cloud-gen">
    <title>Generating the Word Cloud</title>

    <p>
      Once we have the term-document matrix, we need to do a little preparation to get our
      data ready for the word cloud generator. The function expects two vectors as input
      arguments: the first a list of the terms, and the second a list of the frequencies of
      occurrence of the terms, sorted with the most frequent terms appearing first:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch13-wordcloud">
      <code>
EnsurePackage("wordcloud")
tdMatrix &lt;- as.matrix(tweetTDM)
sortedMatrix &lt;- sort(rowSums(tdMatrix), decreasing=TRUE)
cloudFrame &lt;- data.frame(
  word=names(sortedMatrix), freq=sortedMatrix)
wordcloud(cloudFrame$word, cloudFrame$freq)
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      If you recall the Twitter search that we used to retrieve those tweets (<c>#solar</c>)
      it makes perfect sense that <q>solar</q> is the most frequent term. The next most
      popular term is <q>energy</q> and after that there are a variety of related words
      such as <q>independence,</q> <q>green,</q> and <q>wind.</q>
    </p>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch13">
    <title>Chapter Challenge</title>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-challenge">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Develop a function that builds upon previous functions we have developed, such as
          <c>TweetFrame()</c> and <c>CleanTweets()</c>, to take a search term, conduct a
          Twitter search, clean up the resulting texts, formulate a term-document matrix,
          and submit resulting term frequencies to the <c>wordcloud()</c> function. This
          would be a <q>turnkey</q> package that would take a Twitter search term and
          produce a word cloud from it.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>

